div.div: Preparing Children to Learn and Succeed in a Changing World.

span.div:
Dear District 57 Families and Staff,
I hope this letter finds you and your family healthy and safe. As you have probably heard, Gov. Pritzker announced today that Illinois school buildings will remain closed for the rest of the school year, to help slow the spread of COVID-19 throughout the state. This means District 57 will continue remote learning until our last day of school on June 2, and all of our spring activities and events are cancelled.

div.br: I want you to know that I share your disappointment over this news. Many of us expected that this announcement was coming, and we understand it is necessary in light of the current public health crisis. But that doesn’t change the fact that we wanted more than anything for students and staff to be able to finish the year together IN their school buildings, where they belong. Fairview, Lions Park, Lincoln and Westbrook are special places where your children learn and grow every day; they are also where close personal relationships are built – and that’s one of the things that makes this time away so difficult. I know staff members miss their students and coworkers, and students miss their teachers and peers. But District 57 is committed to making sure our learning and connections to each other continue – and, in fact, flourish as much as possible. I have confidence we will be successful in this, thanks to what I’ve seen over the last few weeks -- the hard work of administrators and staff, the partnership of parents and guardians, and the engagement of students.

We will continue to send remote learning updates and assignments via email and the website each week. We are monitoring how things are going and searching for ways to improve and enhance the system and lessons as we go. We’ll keep you informed as any changes are made. The next remote learning communication will go out tomorrow (Saturday), with grading policy and calendar updates.

My staff and I are here to support District families as needed. If you are facing significant challenges and would like someone from the District to contact you, let us know here and we will be in touch as soon as possible. If you are having technical issues or could benefit from an additional device, submit this form. Also, we continue to provide lunches for kids in need. Simply pick up at Lincoln door 1 between 11:30 and 1 on Mondays and Thursdays.

We are all affected by today’s news in different ways. I’m thinking of our fifth- and eighth-grade students and their families, who had hoped to spend these last weeks of school with the teachers and friends who have been such an important part of their lives for all these years. Unfortunately, the year will not end as we had wanted, but I hope you’ll still celebrate and look forward to the many good things to come. We have not yet decided what to do about eighth-grade graduation. We are working on some options and also looking to see how Prospect High School decides to handle its graduation. We will let eighth-grade parents know as soon as we have something to report.

We’re learning from doctors and scientists that the actions we’re taking today do work. I encourage everyone to continue to practice social distancing. We will make it through this! And when we do return to school and get back to our lives, just think of what a special time it will be and the appreciation we’ll have. Thank you for your continued patience and understanding!
